Summary of issues I found (short):

RangeException
Not derived from std::exception; message formatting is minimal.
m_dim in exceptions is always 1 because dim() is not virtual and callers throw from base class context.
dim()/m_dim handling
dim() is implemented non-virtually in base class; derived classes define their own m_dim but base functions (used in exception) call the base dim().
Some templates pass a D parameter but it's not used consistently.
operator[] and const-correctness
A1D provides only non-const operator[]; no const overload.
Index types and bounds
Uses int for indices and bounds; better to use std::size_t for sizes/indices.
begin()/end() naming
begin()/end() return numeric indices (not iterators). This is confusing and collides with iterator semantics. Consider renaming (but keeping names is OK for compatibility).
Header hygiene
using namespace std; present in header (bad practice).
Missing include guards or #pragma once.
main file
Contains infinite while(1) at end, preventing normal exit.
C-style printf mixed with iostream; inconsistent style.
Catch-by-value for RangeException (should catch by const reference).
Minor: formatting, modernizations (constexpr/static constexpr where appropriate), add const overloads, improve exception message.
